    <b>AT&T may pay back Cox, Comcast with cable systems.</b><br>
    <font size=1><b>Date:</b> Tuesday, December 26 @ 10:55:36 CST<br><b>Topic:</b> Broadband<br><br>
    </center><font size=2>
    New York-based AT&T Corp. is believed to be in talks to use cable systems as currency to pay back Atlanta-based Cox Communications Inc. and Philadelphia-based Comcast Corp. for shares in Redwood City, Calif.-based Excite@Home Corp., Reuters reported Sunday. Under terms of a deal made in March, Cox and Comcast have the right to sell 60.4 million shares in the high-speed Internet service back to AT&T for at least $2.9 billion, or $48 a share beginning in 2001. The option expires June 4, 2002. But instead of paying cash for the shares, AT&T may provide payment in the form of cable operations, Retuers reported. 
<br><br>
